-qa.definition: Used to mark the topic of the sentence.

-chu.definition: Negative suffix. Used with mana to form negative statements, or ama to form negative commands.
Interrogative suffix. Used when asking yes-no questions.

-si.definition: Evidential suffix, second-hand information. Indicates that the speaker has not directly experienced the information at hand; hearsay

-s.definition: Evidential suffix, second-hand information. Indicates that the speaker has not directly experienced the information at hand; hearsay

-cha.definition: Factive suffix. Verbalizes nouns (N→V). Expresses that the head noun is being made, built, shaped, turn turned into, added or removed from something else.
Diminutive suffix (N→N). Used to indicate a smaller size or to convey affection.

-chi.definition: <etymology 1 - suffix> Derivational suffix, causative. To make someone do something; to let or allow something.
<etymology 2 - suffix> Used to indicate a putative or conjectural statement.

-chka.definition: Used to indicate a progressive or ongoing action.

-chra.definition: suffix indicating that a speaker infers or conjectures something, as opposed to having direct knowledge of it, or having been told about it

-chá.definition: Used to indicate a putative or conjectural statement.

-kama.definition: Inflectional suffix, limitative. Describes the goal or endpoint of an action; until.

-ku.definition: reflexive suffix: to or for oneself

-m.definition: Evidential suffix, first-hand information. Indicates that the speaker has direct evidence/knowledge of some fact, having experienced it, seen it, heard it, etc.
Used to mark an open-ended question; less formal than -taq.

-man.definition: allative or dative case; indicates the direction of movement or the indirect object
potential mood; indicates possibility or potential

-manta.definition: A suffix for the ablative case. Indicates origin of movement, topic of an utterance, or the makeup of something.

-mi.definition: Evidential suffix, first-hand information. Indicates that the speaker has direct evidence/knowledge of some fact, having experienced it, seen it, heard it, etc.
Used to mark an open-ended question; more informal than -taq

-naya.definition: Desiderative. To want to, to feel like.
Proximative. To be about to, to be close to.

-niku.definition: first First-person exclusive plural subject suffix.

-ntin.definition: Inclusive suffix, similar to English together, with.

-p.definition: Genitive marker following vowels. See also: -pa}}.

-pa.definition: Genitive marker following consonants, except for Ayacucho; see '''Usage notes'''. See also: -p}}.
Indicates a repetitive action. Once more. See also: -paya}}

-paq.definition: A suffix for the dative or benefactive case; "for"

-pi.definition: A suffix for the locative case.

-puni.definition: Indicates certainty, determination, or firm intent

-pura.definition: Suffix for the intrative case; "among, amidst"

-raq.definition: Continuity or permanence. Like English still, yet.

-rayku.definition: Causative. Marks the cause or reason for something. Like English for, because.

-ri.definition: Optionally used to mark the topic of a question. Gives a sense of courtesy.

-rpa.definition: To become. action to be committed. Like English going to

-rqa.definition: Testimonial past. Past tense of personally known facts. Compare to -sqa.

-sqa.definition: Reported past. Past tense of reported facts. Compare to -rqa}}.

-ta.definition: Used for the accusative case. Indicates the direct object of a verb or the goal of a motion verb.
Used to form adverbs from adjectives.

-taq.definition: Used to mark an open-ended question; more polite than mi

-wan.definition: A suffix for the instrumental case.
Indicates the company an action is performed with, with

-y.definition: Nominalizes verbs. The act of doing something. "-ing."
Conjugative suffix for the second second-person imperative mood.

-ykacha.definition: Iterative. Indicates a recurring or repeated action.

-yki.definition: First-person singular subject, second-person singular object marker.

-ysi.definition: Assistive. Indicates that an action helps to complete another action.

-ña.definition: Change or discontinuity. Like English already.

-kuna.definition: Used to form the plural of nouns, when the number or amount is not specified.
